Use this approach:
```
public function destroy($id)
{
    $post = Post::findorfail($id);
    $post-&gt;delete();
    Session::flash(&#39;success&#39;, &#39;The post was just trashed.&#39;);
    return redirect()-&gt;back();
}
```

Even better, take advantage of the [route model binding](https://laravel.com/docs/5.8/routing#implicit-binding).

```
Route::delete(&#39;posts/{post}&#39;, &#39;PostsController@destroy&#39;)-&gt;name(&#39;post.delete&#39;);
```

In the controller:

```
public function destroy(Post $post)
{
    $post-&gt;delete();

    Session::flash(&#39;success&#39;, &#39;The post was just trashed.&#39;);

    return redirect()-&gt;back();
}
```

This will use `findOrFail` behind the scenes, so it will throw 404 if the post does not exist.

To use it in your view:

```
&lt;form method=&quot;post&quot; action=&quot;{{ route(&#39;post.delete&#39;, $post) }}&quot;&gt;
    @csrf
    @method(&#39;delete&#39;)    

    &lt;button type=&quot;submit&quot;&gt;Delete&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;
```

&gt; Call to a member function delete() on null

This error message means that you are trying to call method of the object which is  **not exist. null object.**

in this case, `Post::find($id)` returns **null**. because it couldn&#39;t find any record which is `$id`.

so your `$post` varaiable is null.

to dismiss the error messages, check `$post` variable is null.



    public function destroy($id)
    {
        $post = Post::find($id);

        if(empty($post)) {
            return;
        }

        $post-&gt;delete();
        Session::flash(&#39;success&#39;, &#39;The post was just trashed.&#39;);
    
        return redirect()-&gt;back();
    }

There are many ways to handle that as other answer and Here is another way! Which I prefer to use.

    public function destroy($id)
    {
    
        $validator = Validator::make(compact(&#39;id&#39;), [
            &#39;id&#39; =&gt; &#39;required|int|exists:posts,id&#39;
        }
    
        if ($validator-&gt;fails()) {
            return response([ERROR_MESSAGE], [ERROR_CODE]);
        }
        
        $post = Post::find($id)-&gt;delete();
        return response([SUCCESS_MESSAGE], [SUCCESS_CODE]);
    }

&amp; To be more careful it&#39;s always better to put your code in &quot;Try catch&quot;.

    public function destroy($id)
    {
        $post = Post::find($id);

        if(is_null($post)) {
            abort(404);
        }

        $post-&gt;delete();

        Session::flash(&#39;success&#39;, &#39;The post was just trashed.&#39;); 
   
        return redirect()-&gt;back();
    }

The best practice is to use `findOrFail` helper function in laravel. You can handle exception is Post does not exist and show specific error message in front as below,

use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\ModelNotFoundException;

    public function destroy($id)
    {
    	// Will return a ModelNotFoundException if no user with that id
    	try
    	{
    	    $post = Post::findOrFail($id);
    	    $post-&gt;delete();
    	    Session::flash(&#39;success&#39;, &#39;The post was just trashed.&#39;);
    	    return redirect()-&gt;back();
    	}
    	// catch(Exception $e) catch any exception
    	catch(ModelNotFoundException $e)
    	{
    	    Session::flash(&#39;error&#39;, &#39;The post does not exist.&#39;);
    	    return redirect()-&gt;back();
    	}
    }

This way your app will never crash. Hope this helps!

